value.0: A very fat, gruff looking man, Marigath still grumbles faintly about being sent to work with mushrooms for a time. His clothes, and his belly, are once again covered in grease, and he seems to be at least a little happy to be back in a kitchen.

Woven intricately of fine black silks, blackened leathers, and steel, this armor is so light that it is even more comfortable than normal clothing.  It is also crafted so finely, that the wearer's agility seems to be improved. A mage has had his hand in it's making at some point, because it seems to have magical properties.

An ominous figure looms over you, scrutinizing your every move. The sword it holds is clearly too unwieldy for any mortal being to make proper use of, and given the nature of Tarkuul, is likely some form of undead.

This helmet has been exquisitely forged from adamantine, its sinisterly beautiful design typical of drow craftsmanship. A small letter "V" has been interwoven into the pattern upon the visor.

Adamantine is an extraordinarily hard alloy that is almost impenetrable to normal weapons. Deposits of adamant are usually found near areas of Faerzress in the Underdark, and to the Deep Denizens it is usually black in colour, though it possesses a green sheen when viewed by natural light or a purple-white sheen when viewed by magical light.

A mountain of a man, clad in a very old style of military uniform that bears no obvious rank or insignia. This figure truly towers above the average human, and you're not even sure it is human underneath all that armor.

This horrifying blade was forged by evil, for evil.  It is ever hungry, and is believed to have a dark wizards soul entrapped in the steel.  As it strikes an opponent, the sword hums and drains its victim of their very mind...until they are left as a quivering mass of flesh, with the mind of a beast.  Only the darkest of souls would use this abomination on another living creature.
Udok-Oglar seems rather runty as ogres go, but clear intelligence burns within his eyes.
These robes are infused with a darkly, vile magic, and they're splatted with much blood. You absently wonder about their creation.

In a town by the water
There is an old tale,
Of a monster yet seen long ago.
It was the worry of Kings
And unspoken things,
A nightmare that all seemed to harken...
...'twas the Kraken!

The beast was a shrouded dark
Figure in water,
With tendrils of deadly promises.
It took ships by the dozen
Waters did roughen,
For the town all things seemed to darken...
...'twas the Kraken!

Brave men did set sail all armed
and feeling ready,
To shoot it with a score of harpoons.
But the monster did kill them
Ripping head from stem,
And threw them as food for the shark'en...
...'twas the Kraken!

A cunning bright plan was thought
Up by a sailor,
To join up the lightning to the sea.
So men went out to kill it
Perhaps just lure it,
And what died when the sky did sparken?
...'twas the Kraken!

The town is doing well and
Never forgotten,
Is the tale of the ghostly kraken.
Only the story remains
But words to stay sane,
Whispered from them as they embarken?
"...'twas the Kraken!"

The night is black as kraken's ink,
You'll get lost on your way back home,
Your harpoons will break on the rocks
You'll swing from the ropes alone.

Your hair will fall off of your scalp
And your knife out of its sheathe,
Your blood will rust on your dry bones
You'll eat with wooden teeth.

So, fill your glass up with the ocean
And swallow the fish out of the sea.
I'll put sand inside your pockets
And you can sing along with me:
Tomorrow is black as kraken's ink
~But who the hell needs a compass?~
It's just a lovely day that never comes.

Your lovers are decomposing
And your friends will all go too
Just leave your nightmares at the door
And get lost with us in suit.

Time won't stop to give you
The things that you seek.
Be glad you have what you do now
Cuz nothing is yours to keep.

Fill your glass up with the ocean
And swallow the fish out of the sea.
I'll put some sand inside your pockets
And you can sing along with me:
Tomorrow is black as kraken's ink
~But who the hell needs a compass?~
It's just a lovely day that never comes.

This seems to be a cheap, light beer that's only notable quality is the ease at which it goes down. This makes it popular for sailors and soldiers looking to get drunk quickly and cheaply. The beer isn't terrible, strictly speaking, but it's greenish hue can be somewhat off-putting. Its hang-overs, however, are positivity brutal. The kegs it's tapped from are unmarked.

The label on this keg advertises a premium mead, made from an exotic mix of nightshade and lotus honey from the shadowy gardens of Thultanthar. Whether truth or fiction, the darkly amber mead is potently intoxicating and mildly hallucinogenic. It has a richly bittersweet taste, with a floral aroma and a hint of fruit. Too much of this beverage is known to be unpleasantly toxic.

This key holds an opaque liquid with a milky-white opalescence which lends itself to it's namesake. Once poured, the ivory tendrils swirl around the glass like a spirit, as though incapable of mixing completely. The smell is sickly sweet though it leaves eyes and nostrils stinging, giving the impression that the sweet is masking something much more acrid. This potent liquor goes down easily and at first has a prevalent saccharine taste, though a stinging sensation follows soon after. It is deceptively easy to drink in vast quantities because the only thing that seems to dull the strong and sometimes painful aftertaste is the liquid itself. This seems to be a house brew.

This carefully sealed bottle holds a dark, viscous substance within, most likely the ink of some sea creature. The positioning of the bottle on the mantle of the stage is not unlike how a game hunter might display one of their trophies.

Value.value: Near as you can tell the ink is likely from some sort of giant squid or the like, perhaps merely a thematic decoration for the tavern.
You seem to recall hearing some snippet of tavern gossip that some kind of giant sea creature attacked the Living City at some point, though it seemed more a tall tale than anything else.

You're certain this ink must be from the deadly kraken which threatened the Living City some time ago, slain by its defenders in a heated battle. Perhaps this ink belongs to the very same creature the tavern is named for.

Step up to a plate and the dealer will call for a new game to begin in the next 30 seconds.

Anyone who wants to join in the game should also step up to one of the empty plates around the table.

The dealer will call for each roll of the dice and each participant should throw their dice onto the plate when called.

If you roll a Dirty One Eye (1) you automatically lose the round. The object is to get the closest to 16 without actually hitting 16, between 3 dice rolls. The dealer will ask if you want to "stand" with the number you have.

In the event of a tie, all players will play again.

Appearing more as a purple outline of a weapon than an object of substance, this blade is truly bizarre to behold. It floats weightlessly an inch above the fountain, a certain wrongness about it.

Atop the blade rests a single feather of white and mottled grey.

Value.value: You're not sure of its significance, but the feather atop the blade appears to be a seagull feather.

The significance of what you know to be a seagull feather is unclear, but the blade itself seems to be one of the fabled blades of the paradoxical beings created by Collin Reyes' manipulation of the timeline.

One of the fabled blades of the paradoxical beings created by Collin Reyes' manipulation of the timeline, the seagull feather atop it may signify the attempt of an assassin named Livingston to end Reyes' life, but it's uncertain.
